<div id="review_39156248" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/39156248" />
    <a title="Derek" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1769635-derek"><img alt="Derek" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1232848809p2/1769635.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/39156248?book_show_action=true">Dec 02, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Derek" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Derek" href="/user/show/1769635-derek">Derek</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1769635-derek?shelf=dying-earth">dying-earth</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer39156248" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5746275883600058984">I was drawn into <i>Viriconium</i> by an old paperback copy of <i>The Pastel City</i>, which I thought was a fantastic read.<br/><br/>Little did I know that Harrison had other ideas for the others in the series. He subverts the tropes of a Tolkien-style fantasy by refusing to construct a consistent world; each story must be read by itself, and is an ever-fading echo of the original telling, more baroque and ornate each repetition. The scale shrinks from a world-traveling conflict to intimate character pieces in an almo</span>
  <span id="freeText5746275883600058984" style="display:none">I was drawn into <i>Viriconium</i> by an old paperback copy of <i>The Pastel City</i>, which I thought was a fantastic read.<br /><br />Little did I know that Harrison had other ideas for the others in the series. He subverts the tropes of a Tolkien-style fantasy by refusing to construct a consistent world; each story must be read by itself, and is an ever-fading echo of the original telling, more baroque and ornate each repetition. The scale shrinks from a world-traveling conflict to intimate character pieces in an almost Dickensian style.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5746275883600058984" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


