    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3344555365" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3344555365" />
    <a title="M." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/53418998-m"><img alt="M." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1469451249p2/53418998.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3344555365?book_show_action=true">Nov 11, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="M." class="user" itemprop="url" name="M." href="/user/show/53418998-m">M.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3344555365" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9656682474743397461">The Viriconium series starts out as a subversion of the usual fantasy/sword and sorcery elements. The first novel was quite charming and very entertaining though not without a high degree of creativity. Though the writing is quite playful, it still manages to layer it&apos;s themes as overtones or maybe undertones throughout the narrative. <br/><br/>If you&apos;re reading the edition that I have, the short stories will be woven in and around the novels and although Harrison starts out providing you with a limited h</span>
  <span id="freeText9656682474743397461" style="display:none">The Viriconium series starts out as a subversion of the usual fantasy/sword and sorcery elements. The first novel was quite charming and very entertaining though not without a high degree of creativity. Though the writing is quite playful, it still manages to layer it's themes as overtones or maybe undertones throughout the narrative. <br /><br />If you're reading the edition that I have, the short stories will be woven in and around the novels and although Harrison starts out providing you with a limited hints of a sequence and the tolkienesque, he quickly abandons it. So, throughout the series as it gets weird, and believe me, it gets weird, not only does he subvert the genre and writing styles but he also subverts your tools as a reader to predict, infer and process his writing style. <br />The second novel "A Storm of Wings" is where this really takes hold. Harrsion weaves his prose as effortlessly as your backyard creepy crawly. Setting it up very carefully and calculated only to tear it down and rebuild something else as you move through the series. The 2nd novel seems like a psychedelic piece verging on sci-fi. I had to re-read sections and even go back to previous chapters to wrap my head around it.<br /><br />The last novel is quite short and is pretty kafkaesque in it's tone and there's no swords or sorcery. Rather, many poets and artists occupy Viriconium and it's interesting to compare how the series started out. From The Lord Tegius Cromis, the greatest swordsman to ever live who considers himself a better poet than soldier, to the utter weirdness of the rest of the series. The task of explaining this series is too difficult for me let alone Neil Gaiman who wrote the foreword.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9656682474743397461" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


