  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>

    </div>
  </div>
    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1074114" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1074114" />
    <a title="Lura" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/78475-lura"><img alt="Lura" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1074114?book_show_action=true">May 06, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lura" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lura" href="/user/show/78475-lura">Lura</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">readers into fantasy and postmodernism</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1074114" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2974266881592145260">It&apos;s 3 novels and bunch of short stories in one, and each is pretty distinct. The first novel is formulaic fantasy, not bad, but nothing special, and absolutely not worth the effort of learning silly names and made up history/geography. The second really creates an interesting, almost despairing atmosphere of loss and emptiness that haunts the rest of the series. Nice, twisting plot. Third novel also has a great concept, but most of the plot is tedious. The short stories vary, some bored me, but</span>
  <span id="freeText2974266881592145260" style="display:none">It's 3 novels and bunch of short stories in one, and each is pretty distinct. The first novel is formulaic fantasy, not bad, but nothing special, and absolutely not worth the effort of learning silly names and made up history/geography. The second really creates an interesting, almost despairing atmosphere of loss and emptiness that haunts the rest of the series. Nice, twisting plot. Third novel also has a great concept, but most of the plot is tedious. The short stories vary, some bored me, but some really caught the feel of the last two novels, but were more to the point. I gather that I'm supposed to find Harrison brilliant, but something about his writing put me off a little. I couldn't properly enjoy even the most interesting, creative parts. I might give his non-genre writing a go, but I don't think I could stomach more of his fantasy with the Lovecraft-esque language. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2974266881592145260" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

