    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_687860623" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/687860623" />
    <a title="Edward Rathke" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5657249-edward-rathke"><img alt="Edward Rathke" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442510992p2/5657249.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/687860623?book_show_action=true">Aug 06, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Edward Rathke" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Edward Rathke" href="/user/show/5657249-edward-rathke">Edward Rathke</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5657249-edward-rathke?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer687860623" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1579076611981830198">A pretty uneven collection of novels and stories, but, I think, ultimately brilliant. I did individual reviews of each of the books that make up the cycle elsewhere, except for the short stories which follow the novels. Like the novels, they&apos;re a mix in quality, but always interesting, always linguistically awesome. I find that this is the kind of genre fiction I love. The kind that redefines its genre and world as it progresses. Like Le Guin&apos;s Earthsea or Delany&apos;s Neveryon, Viriconium is set in</span>
  <span id="freeText1579076611981830198" style="display:none">A pretty uneven collection of novels and stories, but, I think, ultimately brilliant. I did individual reviews of each of the books that make up the cycle elsewhere, except for the short stories which follow the novels. Like the novels, they're a mix in quality, but always interesting, always linguistically awesome. I find that this is the kind of genre fiction I love. The kind that redefines its genre and world as it progresses. Like Le Guin's Earthsea or Delany's Neveryon, Viriconium is set in a world that refuses to be pinned down or defined, and instead inverts and rewrites itself almost continuously.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1579076611981830198" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


